WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.750
(whimsical tone)

2
00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:10.410
<v Moderator>Dr. Bestie is coming back for one final</v>

3
00:00:10.410 --> 00:00:15.410
pediatric presentation as we look at issues

4
00:00:15.630 --> 00:00:20.620
related to fever and infectious diseases in kids.

5
00:00:23.340 --> 00:00:26.550
Okay, Jan, take it away.

6
00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:27.383
Bring us home for the day.

7
00:00:27.383 --> 00:00:29.520
<v ->Okay, so we're gonna talk about sick kids this time.</v>

8
00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:31.800
I still don't have anything to disclose.

9
00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:34.680
We're gonna talk mostly about fever,

10
00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:36.210
illnesses of the respiratory tract,

11
00:00:36.210 --> 00:00:40.230
and then some rashes, viral rashes, or infectious rashes.

12
00:00:40.230 --> 00:00:41.280
So let's start with fever.

13
00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:43.093
What is the definition of a fever?

14
00:00:43.093 --> 00:00:45.030
A fever is a condition of the body

15
00:00:45.030 --> 00:00:47.040
characterized by a rise in temperature,

16
00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:48.120
quickening of the pulse,

17
00:00:48.120 --> 00:00:50.250
and disturbance of various body functions.

18
00:00:50.250 --> 00:00:51.270
Really, what do we all wanna know?

19
00:00:51.270 --> 00:00:52.170
It's a number.

20
00:00:52.170 --> 00:00:56.730
Fever is greater than or equal to a hundred 0.4 rectally.

21
00:00:56.730 --> 00:00:59.670
So it doesn't indicate serious illness.

22
00:00:59.670 --> 00:01:01.680
It doesn't mean that they're gonna have brain damage.

23
00:01:01.680 --> 00:01:03.360
It does help to fight infection.

24
00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:04.992
Fever is fabulous.

25
00:01:04.992 --> 00:01:08.070
So let's talk about fever specifically in infants.

26
00:01:08.070 --> 00:01:09.810
So if you have a fever,

27
00:01:09.810 --> 00:01:12.360
rectal temperature of greater than a hundred,

28
00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:14.310
greater than or equal to a hundred 0.4,

29
00:01:16.110 --> 00:01:17.310
probably all of you remember this

30
00:01:17.310 --> 00:01:18.540
from med school and residency,

31
00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:20.160
they get admitted to the hospital.

32
00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:21.900
This is your full septic workup,

33
00:01:21.900 --> 00:01:25.350
they get a CBC, blood cultures, chest x-ray, urinalysis,

34
00:01:25.350 --> 00:01:27.570
urine culture, lumbar puncture.

35
00:01:27.570 --> 00:01:30.060
Nowadays, we also can add a procalcitonin

36
00:01:30.060 --> 00:01:32.430
or a C-reactive protein if that's available.

37
00:01:32.430 --> 00:01:35.430
HSV studies, which I do now pretty much all the time

38
00:01:35.430 --> 00:01:38.310
after my scary outcome I had before.

39
00:01:38.310 --> 00:01:41.370
And there actually is a newborn sepsis calculator,

40
00:01:41.370 --> 00:01:42.480
if you're not familiar with it,

41
00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:45.450
if you use that, it can decrease excessive antibiotic use.

42
00:01:45.450 --> 00:01:47.220
It's really great right after delivery.

43
00:01:47.220 --> 00:01:49.890
We use that on all of our brand new newborns.

44
00:01:49.890 --> 00:01:51.690
Why do we, what do we worry about?

45
00:01:51.690 --> 00:01:54.090
We worry about things that come from mom.

46
00:01:54.090 --> 00:01:56.580
So, it makes sense that in those first 21 days,

47
00:01:56.580 --> 00:01:59.610
group B strep, e coli, listeria, herpes,

48
00:01:59.610 --> 00:02:01.350
these are things that come from mom

49
00:02:01.350 --> 00:02:02.520
during the delivery process.

50
00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:04.410
And the antibiotics have not changed.

51
00:02:04.410 --> 00:02:05.910
It's still amp and gent.

52
00:02:05.910 --> 00:02:08.760
It's still amp and cefotaxime.

53
00:02:08.760 --> 00:02:10.140
These are the same antibiotics they were

54
00:02:10.140 --> 00:02:12.270
when I was in medical school a very long time ago.

55
00:02:12.270 --> 00:02:14.610
You do add vancomycin if you're concerned about

56
00:02:14.610 --> 00:02:16.534
streptococcus pneumonia and meningitis.

57
00:02:16.534 --> 00:02:18.660
You may add acyclovir if your

58
00:02:18.660 --> 00:02:21.180
level suspicion is high for herpes.

59
00:02:21.180 --> 00:02:22.350
You don't use ceftriaxone

60
00:02:22.350 --> 00:02:24.450
because of the risk of chronic (indistinct).

61
00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:26.820
So let's talk about the kids who are

62
00:02:26.820 --> 00:02:28.470
over the age of 21 days.

63
00:02:28.470 --> 00:02:30.423
So three weeks to three months.

64
00:02:31.350 --> 00:02:32.550
If they look abnormal,

65
00:02:32.550 --> 00:02:34.020
so they have poor rousability,

66
00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:35.250
poor caregiver interaction,

67
00:02:35.250 --> 00:02:36.300
their breathing is abnormal,

68
00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:38.010
it's too fast, it's too slow,

69
00:02:38.010 --> 00:02:39.270
their circulation is poor,

70
00:02:39.270 --> 00:02:42.000
they have poor capillary refill,

71
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:43.170
they're modeled looking,

72
00:02:43.170 --> 00:02:45.480
all of those kids, you basically just lump 'em

73
00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:47.460
back in the same category as the kids

74
00:02:47.460 --> 00:02:49.110
under the age of 21 days.

75
00:02:49.110 --> 00:02:51.600
Admit to the hospital, full septic workup.

76
00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:53.580
So this group is easy.

77
00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:55.800
Ooh, let's talk about the ones that aren't quite so easy.

78
00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:59.970
So this is your kids between 21 days and 90 days,

79
00:02:59.970 --> 00:03:03.240
or three weeks and three months, who look well.

80
00:03:03.240 --> 00:03:04.477
You know. They, have a fever, but mom's like,

81
00:03:04.477 --> 00:03:06.030
"I don't know, kid's been acting fine.

82
00:03:06.030 --> 00:03:07.440
Everybody else, no one's sick in the house.

83
00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:08.970
So I don't know what's going on."

84
00:03:08.970 --> 00:03:10.260
So there's a couple of things you can do.

85
00:03:10.260 --> 00:03:13.050
This is called the step-by-step approach.

86
00:03:13.050 --> 00:03:15.150
You wanna do three main things.

87
00:03:15.150 --> 00:03:15.990
You check their urine.

88
00:03:15.990 --> 00:03:17.340
Do they have leukocytes?

89
00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:20.040
Nope. You can get a procalcitonin.

90
00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:21.750
Is it elevated? Nope.

91
00:03:21.750 --> 00:03:24.343
You can check their CRP or their absolute neutrophil count.

92
00:03:24.343 --> 00:03:25.560
Are those elevated?

93
00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:30.090
If not, you actually can say they're at low risk

94
00:03:30.090 --> 00:03:31.470
for invasive bacterial disease,

95
00:03:31.470 --> 00:03:34.080
and you could potentially treat them as an outpatient.

96
00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:35.790
Now all of those things have to be no,

97
00:03:35.790 --> 00:03:37.770
and you have to have reliable parents

98
00:03:37.770 --> 00:03:40.050
who have transportation, who have a phone,

99
00:03:40.050 --> 00:03:42.000
who can figure out how to take a temperature.

100
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:43.830
There's a lot of things that you have to

101
00:03:43.830 --> 00:03:45.930
use your, your judgment to say,

102
00:03:45.930 --> 00:03:47.490
is this somebody that we can manage at home

103
00:03:47.490 --> 00:03:48.480
and follow-up at home?

104
00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:51.063
Now, if any of those are yeses,

105
00:03:52.140 --> 00:03:54.090
then they go right back into the same category

106
00:03:54.090 --> 00:03:54.923
as the younger children,

107
00:03:54.923 --> 00:03:56.790
and they get admitted to the hospital

108
00:03:56.790 --> 00:03:58.173
for a full septic workup.

109
00:03:59.310 --> 00:04:02.073
Okay. So fever can cause seizures.

110
00:04:03.180 --> 00:04:04.770
Not an insignificant number of kids

111
00:04:04.770 --> 00:04:06.750
will have febrile seizures.

112
00:04:06.750 --> 00:04:09.360
Usually in the toddler period,

113
00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:10.470
there are two different kinds.

114
00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:12.870
There's the simple ones which last less than 15 minutes,

115
00:04:12.870 --> 00:04:15.480
and they're your standard generalized tonic-clonic seizure.

116
00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:16.460
They happen just once.

117
00:04:16.460 --> 00:04:18.180
Everyone is terrified.

118
00:04:18.180 --> 00:04:21.510
911 is called, it's very, very frightening.

119
00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:22.740
Then you have complex seizures

120
00:04:22.740 --> 00:04:24.690
which last longer and maybe focal,

121
00:04:24.690 --> 00:04:27.810
and/or they recur in the 24 hours.

122
00:04:27.810 --> 00:04:29.973
So if a child has had a febrile seizure,

123
00:04:29.973 --> 00:04:33.300
they are more likely to have another febrile seizure.

124
00:04:33.300 --> 00:04:35.292
Oh, look at this family history, huh?

125
00:04:35.292 --> 00:04:36.300
What do you know?

126
00:04:36.300 --> 00:04:37.500
And obviously if the child

127
00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:40.290
has an underlying neurological condition, it does,

128
00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:41.970
it's not associated with brain damage.

129
00:04:41.970 --> 00:04:45.660
And this is the hardest thing to convince parents.

130
00:04:45.660 --> 00:04:48.480
If it's a simple febrile seizure,

131
00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:50.460
there's no other evaluation that needs to be done

132
00:04:50.460 --> 00:04:52.290
besides figuring out what caused the fever.

133
00:04:52.290 --> 00:04:53.490
Do they have an ear infection?

134
00:04:53.490 --> 00:04:54.780
Do they have pneumonia?

135
00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:56.730
What else is going on that caused 'em to have the fever?

136
00:04:56.730 --> 00:04:59.520
The fever. Increased risk of febrile seizure

137
00:04:59.520 --> 00:05:02.670
if the MMR is given later rather than earlier.

138
00:05:02.670 --> 00:05:03.900
When I try to argue with my parents

139
00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:05.220
who wanna spread out their vaccines,

140
00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:07.290
I'm like, "Hmm, better give that MMR earlier

141
00:05:07.290 --> 00:05:09.870
'cause they have a lower seizure risk."

142
00:05:09.870 --> 00:05:11.250
Okay, first question.

143
00:05:11.250 --> 00:05:12.630
Alright, a three-year-old girl presents

144
00:05:12.630 --> 00:05:14.430
with a four day history of fever,

145
00:05:14.430 --> 00:05:16.140
no other symptoms, her ears, throat,

146
00:05:16.140 --> 00:05:17.550
lungs, abdominal exam are normal,

147
00:05:17.550 --> 00:05:19.800
but she just looks kind of puny.

148
00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:21.270
So what would be your next step?

149
00:05:21.270 --> 00:05:22.290
So this is a three-year-old girl.

150
00:05:22.290 --> 00:05:26.070
Would you treat the fever and evaluate her in 24 hours?

151
00:05:26.070 --> 00:05:28.440
Would you order a urinalysis with cultures?

152
00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:29.970
Would you get an abdominal ultrasound,

153
00:05:29.970 --> 00:05:33.003
or would you give her some IV fluids hoping to perk her up?

154
00:05:38.880 --> 00:05:40.980
Okay, good. About a little over half of you realize

155
00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:43.050
that you're gonna order a urinalysis with cultures.

156
00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:44.613
So why is that?

157
00:05:44.613 --> 00:05:47.310
Urinary tract infections are the most common

158
00:05:47.310 --> 00:05:49.230
serious bacterial infection in children

159
00:05:49.230 --> 00:05:50.403
less than age three.

160
00:05:51.450 --> 00:05:52.680
If you don't see a source,

161
00:05:52.680 --> 00:05:54.210
think about a urinary tract infection,

162
00:05:54.210 --> 00:05:55.890
particularly in girls.

163
00:05:55.890 --> 00:05:57.420
Up to 7% of girls,

164
00:05:57.420 --> 00:05:58.328
and 2% of boys will have had

165
00:05:58.328 --> 00:06:01.050
a urinary tract infection by age six.

166
00:06:01.050 --> 00:06:02.520
Now the thing that's frustrating about this,

167
00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:06.060
is you really have to get this by catheterization,

168
00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:07.380
or suprapubic tap,

169
00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:08.970
or if the child is potty trained,

170
00:06:08.970 --> 00:06:11.160
you can send mom in there with the little,

171
00:06:11.160 --> 00:06:14.313
the little container and let her try to catch that urine.

172
00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:18.180
You cannot do the bag urine on babies.

173
00:06:18.180 --> 00:06:19.590
So how do you diagnose this?

174
00:06:19.590 --> 00:06:21.630
They have a urinalysis with pyuria,

175
00:06:21.630 --> 00:06:22.980
and you have a positive culture

176
00:06:22.980 --> 00:06:25.590
of greater than 50,000 colony following units.

177
00:06:25.590 --> 00:06:27.510
So that's your, that's your diagnosis

178
00:06:27.510 --> 00:06:28.590
of a urinary tract infection.

179
00:06:28.590 --> 00:06:30.090
And so your treatment,

180
00:06:30.090 --> 00:06:31.950
these are all treatments that you've seen before.

181
00:06:31.950 --> 00:06:34.020
But you can use your bactrim,

182
00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:37.740
you can use your augmentin,

183
00:06:37.740 --> 00:06:40.263
and you wanna treat 'em for seven to 14 days.

184
00:06:41.220 --> 00:06:44.010
So, when do you do any imaging,

185
00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:46.200
you would do an ultrasound if they had their

186
00:06:46.200 --> 00:06:48.930
first febrile urinary tract infection less than age two.

187
00:06:48.930 --> 00:06:49.763
Why is that?

188
00:06:49.763 --> 00:06:51.158
Because you're concerned that maybe the reason why this kid

189
00:06:51.158 --> 00:06:53.130
had a urinary tract infection is because

190
00:06:53.130 --> 00:06:54.810
there's something anatomically wrong.

191
00:06:54.810 --> 00:06:56.880
So you're looking at that with an ultrasound.

192
00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:59.580
Or if they have more than one urinary tract infection.

193
00:06:59.580 --> 00:07:01.140
So a recurrent UTI.

194
00:07:01.140 --> 00:07:02.870
When do you do a Voiding CystoUrethroGram,

195
00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:05.040
if the ultrasound is abnormal, or again,

196
00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:07.443
if they have a recurrent febrile UTI.

197
00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:13.740
Alright. A 16-year-old patient is evaluated

198
00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:16.290
for a four day history of sore throat,

199
00:07:16.290 --> 00:07:19.050
non-productive cough, and rhinorrhea.

200
00:07:19.050 --> 00:07:22.410
She's afebrile. Her exam reveals enlarged

201
00:07:22.410 --> 00:07:24.210
erythematous tonsils, no exudate.

202
00:07:24.210 --> 00:07:27.603
No lymphadenopathy. Ooh, what is the next step?

203
00:07:27.603 --> 00:07:31.290
Dun, dun, dun, supportive care, rapid strep test,

204
00:07:31.290 --> 00:07:34.443
oral penicillin for 10 days or azithromycin for five days.

205
00:07:39.930 --> 00:07:42.480
Excellent. Y'all knew what the right answer was, right?

206
00:07:42.480 --> 00:07:45.330
Supportive care. So why is that?

207
00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:47.100
So this is the modified center criteria

208
00:07:47.100 --> 00:07:48.930
for group A strep pharyngitis.

209
00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:49.860
Probably a lot of you remember

210
00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:51.780
seeing this back in residency.

211
00:07:51.780 --> 00:07:54.780
So you basically get points for having a fever,

212
00:07:54.780 --> 00:07:58.320
no cough, swollen, tender anterior lymph nodes,

213
00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:00.120
tonsillar swelling, and or exudate.

214
00:08:00.120 --> 00:08:01.320
And then you notice you get a point

215
00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:02.910
if you're three to 14,

216
00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:04.500
Zero points if you're 15 to 44.

217
00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:05.370
And if you're over 45,

218
00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:07.560
you actually get a negative point.

219
00:08:07.560 --> 00:08:09.300
So if you look under the column of the total,

220
00:08:09.300 --> 00:08:10.290
this just tells you what to do.

221
00:08:10.290 --> 00:08:11.610
If they are zero to one points,

222
00:08:11.610 --> 00:08:13.620
no testing or treatment.

223
00:08:13.620 --> 00:08:15.900
Could consider testing them at one

224
00:08:15.900 --> 00:08:18.120
if you really feel like it.

225
00:08:18.120 --> 00:08:19.740
So one thing I wanna point out with kids,

226
00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:21.720
if the points are two to three,

227
00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:24.240
you're gonna test with your rapid antigen detection testing.

228
00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:26.220
But in kids you always wanna also get a culture.

229
00:08:26.220 --> 00:08:29.250
So swap 'em with both Q-tips at the same time.

230
00:08:29.250 --> 00:08:31.770
If the antigen test is negative,

231
00:08:31.770 --> 00:08:33.150
you send the culture out.

232
00:08:33.150 --> 00:08:35.160
That's a little bit different in kids than it is in adults.

233
00:08:35.160 --> 00:08:37.850
And if they're four to five, you just treat 'em.

234
00:08:37.850 --> 00:08:40.770
Okay. Pharyngitis. You're gonna hear a theme.

235
00:08:40.770 --> 00:08:44.550
The most common cause pharyngitis in children is viruses.

236
00:08:44.550 --> 00:08:47.730
Amongst bacterial causes is our group A strep.

237
00:08:47.730 --> 00:08:49.410
So post streptococcal illness,

238
00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:52.560
the things that we worry about, rheumatic fever,

239
00:08:52.560 --> 00:08:56.250
you can treat that with NSAIDs, glomerulonephritis,

240
00:08:56.250 --> 00:08:57.780
they'll come in with gross hematuria,

241
00:08:57.780 --> 00:09:01.110
hypertension and edema, reactive arthritis.

242
00:09:01.110 --> 00:09:02.820
And something some of you may not have heard of,

243
00:09:02.820 --> 00:09:05.850
is pediatric autoimmune neuropsychiatric disorders

244
00:09:05.850 --> 00:09:07.705
associated with streptococcal infections.

245
00:09:07.705 --> 00:09:11.040
Very fondly known as "PANDAS."

246
00:09:11.040 --> 00:09:12.450
So if you have a child who has

247
00:09:12.450 --> 00:09:15.270
an abrupt psychiatric change,

248
00:09:15.270 --> 00:09:17.526
and they recently had a strep infection,

249
00:09:17.526 --> 00:09:18.960
please consider this.

250
00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:20.310
This is a real thing.

251
00:09:20.310 --> 00:09:21.143
So how do you treat this?

252
00:09:21.143 --> 00:09:23.610
You can treat with penicillin or amoxicillin for 10 days.

253
00:09:23.610 --> 00:09:25.230
It prevents rheumatic fever,

254
00:09:25.230 --> 00:09:26.880
but it does not prevent glomerular nephritis.

255
00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:29.280
So you still need to warn your parents

256
00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:30.530
that if they see bloody urine,

257
00:09:30.530 --> 00:09:32.130
or the kid is getting swollen,

258
00:09:32.130 --> 00:09:34.230
they need to come in to be seen.

259
00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:36.600
This is something else that I think is really important.

260
00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:39.660
The Infectious Disease Society of America said that,

261
00:09:39.660 --> 00:09:41.910
that group A strep infection is really

262
00:09:41.910 --> 00:09:44.313
uncommon in children younger than three.

263
00:09:44.313 --> 00:09:46.230
If you're gonna, if you find it in the throat,

264
00:09:46.230 --> 00:09:48.270
it's not infection, it's colonization.

265
00:09:48.270 --> 00:09:50.940
So do not test under the age of three.

266
00:09:50.940 --> 00:09:51.870
We see this all the time.

267
00:09:51.870 --> 00:09:53.275
A 12 month old comes in with strep throat.

268
00:09:53.275 --> 00:09:54.330
They don't have strep throat,

269
00:09:54.330 --> 00:09:56.110
they have strep colonization.

270
00:09:56.110 --> 00:09:59.850
Okay, abscesses you can,

271
00:09:59.850 --> 00:10:01.440
so if they have untreated strep throat,

272
00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:02.520
they can develop an abscess.

273
00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:05.250
They'll have severe throat or neck pain.

274
00:10:05.250 --> 00:10:07.350
They often won't eat, very high fevers.

275
00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:09.273
They have that hot potato voice.

276
00:10:10.110 --> 00:10:11.430
They may not be able to open their mouth.

277
00:10:11.430 --> 00:10:13.440
And the treatment is the same treatment

278
00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:15.870
as for every other abscess under the sun.

279
00:10:15.870 --> 00:10:17.459
You drain it, you can give 'em some IV antibiotics,

280
00:10:17.459 --> 00:10:20.563
maybe some steroids, but it needs to be drained.

281
00:10:20.563 --> 00:10:23.190
Epiglottitis, we don't see this as much anymore,

282
00:10:23.190 --> 00:10:24.510
although maybe we'll start seeing it some more

283
00:10:24.510 --> 00:10:26.670
if people don't vaccinate their kids.

284
00:10:26.670 --> 00:10:29.130
You'll see a swollen cherry red epiglottis.

285
00:10:29.130 --> 00:10:30.210
You see the thumbprint sign.

286
00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:31.830
See how it looks like a little thumb

287
00:10:31.830 --> 00:10:33.333
sort of sticking in like that.

288
00:10:34.470 --> 00:10:35.560
And the key thing with this,

289
00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:38.610
that big epiglottis is gonna occlude their airway

290
00:10:38.610 --> 00:10:39.443
if you don't watch out.

291
00:10:39.443 --> 00:10:42.030
So you need to make sure you have good airway management.

292
00:10:42.030 --> 00:10:44.010
You can treat them with antibiotics.

293
00:10:44.010 --> 00:10:46.050
You don't need steroids or racemic epinephrine.

294
00:10:46.050 --> 00:10:48.360
So it's basically make sure that they breathe,

295
00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:49.610
get 'em some antibiotics.

296
00:10:50.910 --> 00:10:52.971
Oh, now this is something none of us ever sees, right?

297
00:10:52.971 --> 00:10:54.780
Viral upper respiratory infections,

298
00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:56.160
the bane of our existence.

299
00:10:56.160 --> 00:10:58.500
So, for kids, over the counter

300
00:10:58.500 --> 00:11:01.140
cough and cold medicines not indicated.

301
00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:03.420
And actually they cause more harm than good.

302
00:11:03.420 --> 00:11:05.310
So do not recommend over the counter

303
00:11:05.310 --> 00:11:07.872
cough and cold medicines for children under the age of four.

304
00:11:07.872 --> 00:11:08.910
What can you do?

305
00:11:08.910 --> 00:11:10.020
'Cause parents want something to do.

306
00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:12.118
So honey. Honey is actually the best treatment

307
00:11:12.118 --> 00:11:13.939
for cough in this age group.

308
00:11:13.939 --> 00:11:15.450
Over the age of one,

309
00:11:15.450 --> 00:11:16.740
they can put it on toast,

310
00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:18.450
they can mix it into their milk,

311
00:11:18.450 --> 00:11:20.310
they can put it on a spoon and give it to their mouth.

312
00:11:20.310 --> 00:11:21.660
They can, however they wanna have their honey,

313
00:11:21.660 --> 00:11:22.519
they can have honey.

314
00:11:22.519 --> 00:11:25.860
Nasal saline irrigation, there are no side effects.

315
00:11:25.860 --> 00:11:27.240
It just keeps squirting it in their nose,

316
00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:29.850
and they'll snort and buck it out however they can.

317
00:11:29.850 --> 00:11:31.950
Vapor rub over the age of two,

318
00:11:31.950 --> 00:11:34.350
just under the age of two can irritate airways.

319
00:11:34.350 --> 00:11:36.060
And of course all your analgesics.

320
00:11:36.060 --> 00:11:38.370
So Tylenol, ibuprofen, sometimes that's enough

321
00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:39.570
to make 'em feel better.

322
00:11:40.890 --> 00:11:42.480
I don't think I need to say this,

323
00:11:42.480 --> 00:11:46.110
but don't use antibiotics for upper respiratory infections.

324
00:11:46.110 --> 00:11:48.000
That does come up on the boards once in a while.

325
00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.550
Seems like a no brainer, but it should be said.

326
00:11:50.550 --> 00:11:54.090
Lymphadenopathy. 50% of kids will have

327
00:11:54.090 --> 00:11:54.923
some sort of lymphadenopathy.

328
00:11:54.923 --> 00:11:55.756
The parents will come and see

329
00:11:55.756 --> 00:11:56.797
"There's a bump on his neck."

330
00:11:56.797 --> 00:11:57.907
"There's a bump on his head."

331
00:11:57.907 --> 00:11:58.740
"There's a bump here.

332
00:11:58.740 --> 00:11:59.940
I don't know what it is."

333
00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:02.394
Most of the time you can just watch for about a month.

334
00:12:02.394 --> 00:12:04.104
And as long as they aren't having fever,

335
00:12:04.104 --> 00:12:06.637
weight loss, night sweats, sort of your,

336
00:12:06.637 --> 00:12:08.750
"Oh my gosh, they have cancer." kind of symptoms.

337
00:12:08.750 --> 00:12:10.710
If there's a lot of inflammation,

338
00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:12.390
you can try some oral antibiotics.

339
00:12:12.390 --> 00:12:15.240
If it persists, that's when you start your workup.

340
00:12:15.240 --> 00:12:19.590
So you do your CBC, said rate, look at chest x-ray.

341
00:12:19.590 --> 00:12:21.060
If you need to do some imaging,

342
00:12:21.060 --> 00:12:22.680
for younger kids it's ultrasound,

343
00:12:22.680 --> 00:12:24.480
for older kids, it's a CAT scan.

344
00:12:24.480 --> 00:12:28.623
And of course a needle aspiration if it persists.

345
00:12:29.670 --> 00:12:30.810
Ooh, fun pictures.

346
00:12:30.810 --> 00:12:33.540
Okay, not as fun as Gary's, but some fun pictures.

347
00:12:33.540 --> 00:12:37.380
So herpes, you can get herpes gingivos dermatitis.

348
00:12:37.380 --> 00:12:40.410
That's all the like swollen ulcers inside the mouth.

349
00:12:40.410 --> 00:12:41.340
You can see what looks like.

350
00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:42.300
Terrible canker sores.

351
00:12:42.300 --> 00:12:44.280
They have a fever, they have lymphadenopathy,

352
00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:45.260
they don't feel very good.

353
00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:47.779
You do wanna treat them with oral acyclovir.

354
00:12:47.779 --> 00:12:50.850
Then also they can get the standard cold sores

355
00:12:50.850 --> 00:12:52.830
on the lips just like adults can.

356
00:12:52.830 --> 00:12:55.580
Again, teeth, you can treat 'em with topical acyclovir.

357
00:12:57.300 --> 00:13:00.117
Herpangina, which is coxsackie virus,

358
00:13:00.117 --> 00:13:01.680
fever, headaches, sore throat,

359
00:13:01.680 --> 00:13:03.240
may just have these little ulcers in back.

360
00:13:03.240 --> 00:13:04.500
This is actually my daughter's throat.

361
00:13:04.500 --> 00:13:06.180
She used to get a lot of these when she was a kid.

362
00:13:06.180 --> 00:13:08.126
So she's like, "Mom, why are you taking pictures?"

363
00:13:08.126 --> 00:13:10.050
Like I'm gonna show it to thousands

364
00:13:10.050 --> 00:13:11.450
of people you'll never meet.

365
00:13:13.230 --> 00:13:15.480
The benefit of being a a doctor's kid, right?

366
00:13:15.480 --> 00:13:18.000
And then of course your standard canker sores,

367
00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:19.560
which we don't know what causes it.

368
00:13:19.560 --> 00:13:20.593
You treat it symptomatically.

369
00:13:20.593 --> 00:13:22.680
Please consider dexamethasone,

370
00:13:22.680 --> 00:13:25.020
topical dexamethasone for these kids

371
00:13:25.020 --> 00:13:27.210
if they can, you know, swab,

372
00:13:27.210 --> 00:13:28.620
swish it around and spit it out

373
00:13:28.620 --> 00:13:29.453
as opposed to swallowing it.

374
00:13:29.453 --> 00:13:32.280
It does help resolve them a lot faster.

375
00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:34.230
Okay, next question.

376
00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:36.270
Okay, I can almost guarantee you

377
00:13:36.270 --> 00:13:37.485
that the next two things we talk about

378
00:13:37.485 --> 00:13:38.730
will be on your board exam.

379
00:13:38.730 --> 00:13:40.290
So if you've been sort of dozing off,

380
00:13:40.290 --> 00:13:42.367
kind of, whew, wake yourself and pay attention.

381
00:13:42.367 --> 00:13:43.530
"A two year-old child is brought

382
00:13:43.530 --> 00:13:45.630
to the emergency department with a barking cough,

383
00:13:45.630 --> 00:13:47.340
strider that worsened tonight,

384
00:13:47.340 --> 00:13:49.500
and a temperature of 101.

385
00:13:49.500 --> 00:13:51.360
What is the treatment?"

386
00:13:51.360 --> 00:13:53.240
Do you give them nebulized albuterol?

387
00:13:53.240 --> 00:13:55.341
Do you give them inhaled steroid?

388
00:13:55.341 --> 00:13:58.047
Do you do nebulized epinephrine and dexamethasone,

389
00:13:58.047 --> 00:14:00.843
or do you do humidified oxygen?

390
00:14:06.240 --> 00:14:09.660
Alright, nebulized epinephrine and dexamethasone,

391
00:14:09.660 --> 00:14:11.717
because this is, say it together.

392
00:14:11.717 --> 00:14:13.920
<v Group>Croup.</v>
<v ->Croup. Yes, excellent.</v>

393
00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:15.120
This is croup.

394
00:14:15.120 --> 00:14:16.722
So croup is a viral illness.

395
00:14:16.722 --> 00:14:18.210
There's all different causes,

396
00:14:18.210 --> 00:14:20.400
but it causes a edema of the upper airway,

397
00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:22.770
if you can see in this X-ray, there's sort of a,

398
00:14:22.770 --> 00:14:24.810
the airway is narrowed.

399
00:14:24.810 --> 00:14:26.250
They have URI symptoms,

400
00:14:26.250 --> 00:14:28.800
but they have that classic barky cough.

401
00:14:28.800 --> 00:14:30.090
Sounds like a seal.

402
00:14:30.090 --> 00:14:31.487
It's worse at night.

403
00:14:31.487 --> 00:14:33.060
And the problem is sometimes

404
00:14:33.060 --> 00:14:34.380
when they come and see you in the office,

405
00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:35.490
they just look like a cold.

406
00:14:35.490 --> 00:14:36.495
And then the mom says, "Well I took 'em home,

407
00:14:36.495 --> 00:14:38.024
and at 10 o'clock at night they started,

408
00:14:38.024 --> 00:14:39.900
you know, having more problems breathing

409
00:14:39.900 --> 00:14:41.400
and making this barky cough.

410
00:14:41.400 --> 00:14:43.440
So I always ask, say, "Tell me how the cough sounds."

411
00:14:43.440 --> 00:14:45.750
Sometimes I'll actually do the cough.

412
00:14:45.750 --> 00:14:48.030
Entertains them all to no end.

413
00:14:48.030 --> 00:14:49.770
Alright. And you'll see the steeple sign,

414
00:14:49.770 --> 00:14:51.360
the narrowing of the airways.

415
00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:52.980
You don't really need to do any other testing.

416
00:14:52.980 --> 00:14:55.260
Most of the time, this is a completely clinical diagnosis.

417
00:14:55.260 --> 00:14:56.760
You hear the barky cough,

418
00:14:56.760 --> 00:14:57.997
the kid's in the right age group, and you go,

419
00:14:57.997 --> 00:15:00.000
"Yep, that's croup."

420
00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.430
So if you haven't treated croup in a while,

421
00:15:02.430 --> 00:15:04.470
this is important, 'cause this is

422
00:15:04.470 --> 00:15:06.150
a little bit different than how it used to be.

423
00:15:06.150 --> 00:15:08.460
You treat every episode of croup

424
00:15:08.460 --> 00:15:10.680
no matter how mild, with dexamethasone.

425
00:15:10.680 --> 00:15:14.850
And it's 0.15 to 0.6 mgs/kg IM or oral.

426
00:15:14.850 --> 00:15:16.226
It reduces hospitalization rates,

427
00:15:16.226 --> 00:15:18.210
and it shortens ED stays.

428
00:15:18.210 --> 00:15:19.680
One dose. That's all you gotta give 'em.

429
00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:20.730
So if you have it in your office,

430
00:15:20.730 --> 00:15:21.900
you give it to 'em then, if not,

431
00:15:21.900 --> 00:15:22.747
you write a prescription and say,

432
00:15:22.747 --> 00:15:24.720
"Go pick it up and give it to 'em right now

433
00:15:24.720 --> 00:15:25.800
before they go home.

434
00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:27.540
Any severity. So even mild croup,

435
00:15:27.540 --> 00:15:28.762
you would still give this to 'em.

436
00:15:28.762 --> 00:15:31.230
So let's say they have moderate to severe croup.

437
00:15:31.230 --> 00:15:34.290
So bad enough to maybe go to the emergency department,

438
00:15:34.290 --> 00:15:35.400
or they've come into your office,

439
00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:37.133
and you're like, "Whoa, they don't look so good."

440
00:15:37.133 --> 00:15:40.800
You would give them nebulized receiving epinephrine.

441
00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:42.480
You do wanna keep them

442
00:15:42.480 --> 00:15:44.520
under observation for at least four hours.

443
00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:46.770
Most of the time the standard case is

444
00:15:46.770 --> 00:15:47.603
that they come into the

445
00:15:47.603 --> 00:15:48.990
emergency department in the middle of the night,

446
00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:50.160
you get called for admission.

447
00:15:50.160 --> 00:15:51.210
You observe them overnight,

448
00:15:51.210 --> 00:15:53.100
send them home some time during the next day.

449
00:15:53.100 --> 00:15:55.050
You still give them dexamethasone.

450
00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:00.120
Okay, next question.

451
00:16:00.120 --> 00:16:02.130
Also one I can pretty much guarantee

452
00:16:02.130 --> 00:16:05.310
is going to be on your boards.

453
00:16:05.310 --> 00:16:08.310
A nine month old child is admitted in January for cough,

454
00:16:08.310 --> 00:16:09.960
wheezing, feeding difficulty,

455
00:16:09.960 --> 00:16:12.270
and a fever of 38 degrees celsius.

456
00:16:12.270 --> 00:16:16.050
Chest X-ray showed mild parabronchial cuffing.

457
00:16:16.050 --> 00:16:18.780
Which treatment is indicated?

458
00:16:18.780 --> 00:16:22.290
Amoxicillin/clavulanate, systemic corticosteroids,

459
00:16:22.290 --> 00:16:24.570
supplemental oxygen and fluids,

460
00:16:24.570 --> 00:16:26.643
or nebulized ipratropium?

461
00:16:31.890 --> 00:16:34.020
Excellent. Most of you knew that supplemental oxygen

462
00:16:34.020 --> 00:16:35.610
and fluids is the right answer

463
00:16:35.610 --> 00:16:37.950
because this is bronchiolitis.

464
00:16:37.950 --> 00:16:39.360
So croup, bronchiolitis.

465
00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:41.220
If you learn nothing else from this lecture,

466
00:16:41.220 --> 00:16:42.494
pay attention to those two.

467
00:16:42.494 --> 00:16:44.580
So the most common cause of bronchiolitis

468
00:16:44.580 --> 00:16:47.370
and pneumonia is respiratory syncytial virus.

469
00:16:47.370 --> 00:16:48.510
We already talked about there is now

470
00:16:48.510 --> 00:16:50.260
a monoclonal antibody for it.

471
00:16:50.260 --> 00:16:52.220
Woo-hoo. If you can get it.

472
00:16:52.220 --> 00:16:53.919
It looks like a cold,

473
00:16:53.919 --> 00:16:56.400
rhinorrhea, pharyngitis, cough, wheezing.

474
00:16:56.400 --> 00:16:58.291
The biggest thing is they have some wheezing.

475
00:16:58.291 --> 00:16:59.910
And so you're thinking why is this,

476
00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:01.350
you know, young kid wheezing?

477
00:17:01.350 --> 00:17:05.040
You know? they're too young to have asthma, maybe.

478
00:17:05.040 --> 00:17:06.900
But they definitely,

479
00:17:06.900 --> 00:17:09.120
the wheezing is the thing that usually gives this away.

480
00:17:09.120 --> 00:17:11.580
You can do the antigen detection assay for RSV,

481
00:17:11.580 --> 00:17:12.450
especially if you're not sure

482
00:17:12.450 --> 00:17:13.740
if it's the wrong time of the year.

483
00:17:13.740 --> 00:17:15.900
We were doing a lot of those a couple years ago

484
00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:17.800
when we were seeing RSV in the summer.

485
00:17:18.690 --> 00:17:19.890
So the treatment is supportive.

486
00:17:19.890 --> 00:17:22.873
Oxygen, Tylenol, fluids, you can use nebulized

487
00:17:22.873 --> 00:17:25.470
hypertonic saline mixed evidence on that.

488
00:17:25.470 --> 00:17:27.420
You do not use bronchodilators.

489
00:17:27.420 --> 00:17:28.710
You don't give 'em albuterol,

490
00:17:28.710 --> 00:17:30.030
you don't give them steroids,

491
00:17:30.030 --> 00:17:31.320
you don't give 'em any antibiotics.

492
00:17:31.320 --> 00:17:33.120
You basically do supportive treatment.

493
00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:35.820
If they are sick enough to be hospitalized

494
00:17:35.820 --> 00:17:37.230
because of their oxygen levels,

495
00:17:37.230 --> 00:17:38.340
that's the reason why you admit them

496
00:17:38.340 --> 00:17:39.690
is 'cause they need oxygen

497
00:17:39.690 --> 00:17:42.270
until they have recovered enough

498
00:17:42.270 --> 00:17:43.890
to not need oxygen anymore.

499
00:17:43.890 --> 00:17:46.429
We already talked a little bit about nirsevimab.

500
00:17:46.429 --> 00:17:48.870
This actually says it can be given to premature infants,

501
00:17:48.870 --> 00:17:50.670
but actually give it to all infants.

502
00:17:50.670 --> 00:17:53.640
And what we used to know, which was synagis,

503
00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:54.930
you give monthly.

504
00:17:54.930 --> 00:17:58.230
So if you can't get ahold of the nirsevimab,

505
00:17:58.230 --> 00:18:00.990
that's your other alternative for kids who are

506
00:18:00.990 --> 00:18:03.810
born prematurely or have chronic lung disease.

507
00:18:03.810 --> 00:18:08.340
Pertussis, again, starting to see a bit of a resurgence

508
00:18:08.340 --> 00:18:10.296
of this because of decrease in vaccinations

509
00:18:10.296 --> 00:18:11.940
in certain populations.

510
00:18:11.940 --> 00:18:14.520
Why do we admit kids who are under the age of six months,

511
00:18:14.520 --> 00:18:16.800
eh, because 50% of them have become apneic.

512
00:18:16.800 --> 00:18:19.110
That's not something you wanna have happen at home.

513
00:18:19.110 --> 00:18:21.382
They have pneumonia, seizures, and they can die.

514
00:18:21.382 --> 00:18:22.830
So you wanna test.

515
00:18:22.830 --> 00:18:24.660
If you are suspicious of pertussis,

516
00:18:24.660 --> 00:18:26.190
and you're going to treat for pertussis,

517
00:18:26.190 --> 00:18:27.150
you need to test.

518
00:18:27.150 --> 00:18:28.575
This is a reportable disease.

519
00:18:28.575 --> 00:18:29.910
So please make sure you test.

520
00:18:29.910 --> 00:18:31.380
This is for both kids and adults

521
00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:33.530
anytime you think you might have pertussis.

522
00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:36.660
The treatment is supportive.

523
00:18:36.660 --> 00:18:40.290
The antibiotics does not make you get better faster.

524
00:18:40.290 --> 00:18:42.750
It helps decrease the spread to everybody else,

525
00:18:42.750 --> 00:18:44.934
but it does not make you get better faster.

526
00:18:44.934 --> 00:18:46.560
And for your close contacts,

527
00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:48.000
you wanna give them azithromycin.

528
00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:49.200
And of course all of your adults

529
00:18:49.200 --> 00:18:52.680
should have had their TDAP at least once.

530
00:18:52.680 --> 00:18:54.210
Okay, to continue with our theme,

531
00:18:54.210 --> 00:18:58.742
the most common cause of pneumonia in kids are viruses.

532
00:18:58.742 --> 00:19:00.360
We already talked about RSV

533
00:19:00.360 --> 00:19:02.910
is a big one in those younger kids.

534
00:19:02.910 --> 00:19:05.160
You really only need to do a chest x-ray

535
00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:07.350
if their O2 saturation is less than 90%,

536
00:19:07.350 --> 00:19:09.660
or if you're not really sure what's going on.

537
00:19:09.660 --> 00:19:12.210
You don't need to do a chest x-ray for all pneumonias.

538
00:19:12.210 --> 00:19:15.030
You will hospitalize them if they have low oxygen levels,

539
00:19:15.030 --> 00:19:16.770
or if you're thinking they maybe have MRSA,

540
00:19:16.770 --> 00:19:18.000
or obviously if they're in

541
00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:19.860
significant distress or dehydration,

542
00:19:19.860 --> 00:19:23.010
or parents can't seem to treat them as an outpatient.

543
00:19:23.010 --> 00:19:25.920
Your bacterial causes, strep pneumonia, mycoplasmal,

544
00:19:25.920 --> 00:19:28.024
where you would treat with amoxicillin

545
00:19:28.024 --> 00:19:30.450
as your first choice, and azithromycin

546
00:19:30.450 --> 00:19:33.270
or clarithromycin as your second choice.

547
00:19:33.270 --> 00:19:35.391
Gastroenteritis. Guess what? Viruses.

548
00:19:35.391 --> 00:19:38.250
Dr. Weismiller already talked about rotavirus and norovirus.

549
00:19:38.250 --> 00:19:39.600
Your bacterial causes are usually

550
00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:41.223
going to cause bloody diarrhea.

551
00:19:43.260 --> 00:19:44.314
And how do you prevent this?

552
00:19:44.314 --> 00:19:45.300
Oh, look at that.

553
00:19:45.300 --> 00:19:46.716
Breastfeeding. Still good.

554
00:19:46.716 --> 00:19:49.334
Your rotavirus vaccines and washing your hands.

555
00:19:49.334 --> 00:19:51.450
If we've learned nothing over the past few years,

556
00:19:51.450 --> 00:19:53.394
it should be that washing your hands is also good.

557
00:19:53.394 --> 00:19:55.770
If you have signs of dehydration, lethargy,

558
00:19:55.770 --> 00:19:58.983
dry mucus membranes, decreased tears,

559
00:19:59.910 --> 00:20:00.780
I just threw this in here too.

560
00:20:00.780 --> 00:20:01.613
You don't need to do stool studies

561
00:20:01.613 --> 00:20:03.584
unless you've had more than 14 days

562
00:20:03.584 --> 00:20:06.210
of diarrhea or it's bloody diarrhea.

563
00:20:06.210 --> 00:20:07.710
How to treat dehydration.

564
00:20:07.710 --> 00:20:10.320
Half strength apple juice is actually really great.

565
00:20:10.320 --> 00:20:12.120
And then once they can drink

566
00:20:12.120 --> 00:20:13.950
whatever fluids they can keep down,

567
00:20:13.950 --> 00:20:15.360
resume their normal diet,

568
00:20:15.360 --> 00:20:17.970
you can give them a little bit of Zofran.

569
00:20:17.970 --> 00:20:19.380
You can do some probiotics.

570
00:20:19.380 --> 00:20:21.990
Do not give them anti-diarrheals.

571
00:20:21.990 --> 00:20:23.140
Alright, next question.

572
00:20:24.480 --> 00:20:27.758
A two year old boy has very red cheeks and a fine rash,

573
00:20:27.758 --> 00:20:29.127
but does not appear ill.

574
00:20:29.127 --> 00:20:31.050
He had a fever a couple of days ago.

575
00:20:31.050 --> 00:20:33.540
When can he return to daycare?

576
00:20:33.540 --> 00:20:35.123
He has very red cheeks.

577
00:20:35.123 --> 00:20:39.706
Today, tomorrow, five days, or after the rash has gone?

578
00:20:44.130 --> 00:20:49.080
Excellent. Today, because this is fifth disease, right?

579
00:20:49.080 --> 00:20:50.700
The slap cheeks.

580
00:20:50.700 --> 00:20:54.398
So it's very, very, very common caused by parvovirus B19.

581
00:20:54.398 --> 00:20:56.400
The rash is immune mediated.

582
00:20:56.400 --> 00:20:57.690
So usually the kid is sick,

583
00:20:57.690 --> 00:20:58.737
and then the rash appears.

584
00:20:58.737 --> 00:21:02.670
So by the time the rash appears they can go to school.

585
00:21:02.670 --> 00:21:04.920
Usually we don't worry about this too much

586
00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:06.030
except for pregnant women.

587
00:21:06.030 --> 00:21:07.080
They can have fetal hydros,

588
00:21:07.080 --> 00:21:09.240
or fetal demise if they are not immune.

589
00:21:09.240 --> 00:21:10.560
And this is just sort of the phases

590
00:21:10.560 --> 00:21:12.120
that get the slapped cheeks.

591
00:21:12.120 --> 00:21:14.010
They will have this sort of reticular

592
00:21:14.010 --> 00:21:14.970
rash all over of the body.

593
00:21:14.970 --> 00:21:16.680
And the thing to remember that with kids,

594
00:21:16.680 --> 00:21:18.240
is it may pop up again later.

595
00:21:18.240 --> 00:21:20.130
So if they had this in February,

596
00:21:20.130 --> 00:21:21.554
when they go out to the beach in May,

597
00:21:21.554 --> 00:21:22.890
it may pop up again.

598
00:21:22.890 --> 00:21:24.840
So just warn the parents that if it comes up,

599
00:21:24.840 --> 00:21:25.860
it doesn't mean they're sick again,

600
00:21:25.860 --> 00:21:28.830
it's just the body responding again.

601
00:21:28.830 --> 00:21:32.100
Measles, we see this in under vaccinated populations.

602
00:21:32.100 --> 00:21:33.750
They have fever, malaise, anorexia.

603
00:21:33.750 --> 00:21:36.840
And then remember, the four, the four C's,

604
00:21:36.840 --> 00:21:38.790
conjunctivitis, coryza, cough,

605
00:21:38.790 --> 00:21:40.560
and well Koplik starts with a K,

606
00:21:40.560 --> 00:21:42.150
so a little license with that.

607
00:21:42.150 --> 00:21:45.930
This is that macular popu, macular papular rash,

608
00:21:45.930 --> 00:21:48.022
starts on the face and goes down and out,

609
00:21:48.022 --> 00:21:49.653
and these kids are sick.

610
00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:52.433
Why do we care?

611
00:21:52.433 --> 00:21:53.970
Well, there's all kinds of scary complications

612
00:21:53.970 --> 00:21:55.263
that can happen with it.

613
00:21:57.300 --> 00:21:59.370
Roseola, I think when I,

614
00:21:59.370 --> 00:22:01.590
we see roseola obviously way more than we see measles.

615
00:22:01.590 --> 00:22:03.720
I get parents coming in saying, "Is this measles?"

616
00:22:03.720 --> 00:22:06.630
And it's important to be able to know the difference.

617
00:22:06.630 --> 00:22:07.620
A lot of it is the history.

618
00:22:07.620 --> 00:22:09.870
So for this, the kids will often have a fever,

619
00:22:09.870 --> 00:22:12.540
and then otherwise they start to look pretty good.

620
00:22:12.540 --> 00:22:14.130
And by the time they start to look pretty good,

621
00:22:14.130 --> 00:22:16.440
this rash pops out and it can be very frightening.

622
00:22:16.440 --> 00:22:17.460
'Cause the kid is fine one day,

623
00:22:17.460 --> 00:22:19.650
and the next day, boom, they're covered in this,

624
00:22:19.650 --> 00:22:22.260
this maculos all over the trunk.

625
00:22:22.260 --> 00:22:23.730
Here's a picture of it,

626
00:22:23.730 --> 00:22:24.810
and it starts on the trunk

627
00:22:24.810 --> 00:22:26.340
and sort of spreads its way out.

628
00:22:26.340 --> 00:22:28.776
Almost all kids have had this by the age of three.

629
00:22:28.776 --> 00:22:30.840
This is really fun for my medical students,

630
00:22:30.840 --> 00:22:32.220
'cause they come in, "I think it's measles."

631
00:22:32.220 --> 00:22:33.414
I'm like, "Yeah, it's roseola."

632
00:22:33.414 --> 00:22:34.860
Which is good.

633
00:22:34.860 --> 00:22:37.380
Mumps, under vaccinated populations as well.

634
00:22:37.380 --> 00:22:38.910
They have myalgia, fatigue,

635
00:22:38.910 --> 00:22:40.728
loss of appetite, fever, headache.

636
00:22:40.728 --> 00:22:44.070
The most common manifestation is a parotitis.

637
00:22:44.070 --> 00:22:45.810
And complications are infertility.

638
00:22:45.810 --> 00:22:46.950
That's the big one.

639
00:22:46.950 --> 00:22:48.450
That'll show up on the boards.

640
00:22:49.320 --> 00:22:50.700
Henoch-Schonlein Purpura.

641
00:22:50.700 --> 00:22:53.550
90% of cases occur under the age of 10.

642
00:22:53.550 --> 00:22:55.560
So the classic board question will be,

643
00:22:55.560 --> 00:22:57.840
had a child who had a upper respiratory infection

644
00:22:57.840 --> 00:22:59.100
with a little bit of fever, fatigue,

645
00:22:59.100 --> 00:23:01.650
and now they have abdominal pain, arthritis,

646
00:23:01.650 --> 00:23:03.870
and this weird rash on their legs,

647
00:23:03.870 --> 00:23:06.030
and it's macular papular progressing

648
00:23:06.030 --> 00:23:09.180
to purpura on buttocks and legs.

649
00:23:09.180 --> 00:23:10.456
The reason why we care about this

650
00:23:10.456 --> 00:23:12.810
is because renal disease is pretty common.

651
00:23:12.810 --> 00:23:14.340
About half of kids will get renal disease.

652
00:23:14.340 --> 00:23:16.980
You wanna check for hematuria, proteinuria in these kids,

653
00:23:16.980 --> 00:23:19.030
and you wanna treat with oral prednisone.

654
00:23:20.460 --> 00:23:22.020
Hand, Foot, and Mouth Disease.

655
00:23:22.020 --> 00:23:24.570
We all see this usually in kids less than five.

656
00:23:24.570 --> 00:23:25.403
Although guess what?

657
00:23:25.403 --> 00:23:26.400
They give it to their parents.

658
00:23:26.400 --> 00:23:29.206
And their parents are really miserable when they get this.

659
00:23:29.206 --> 00:23:33.690
It's coxsackie virus, oral fecal spread.

660
00:23:33.690 --> 00:23:35.220
They have fever, sore throat, anorexia,

661
00:23:35.220 --> 00:23:37.590
and then boom, a rash shows up on the palms

662
00:23:37.590 --> 00:23:39.900
and the soles of the feet,

663
00:23:39.900 --> 00:23:41.880
also shows up on the butt for little babies.

664
00:23:41.880 --> 00:23:42.713
So that's called,

665
00:23:42.713 --> 00:23:45.960
Hand, Foot, Mouth and Butt Disease, jokingly.

666
00:23:45.960 --> 00:23:47.130
And it'll go away.

667
00:23:47.130 --> 00:23:49.950
Mostly the kids, if their mouth really hurts,

668
00:23:49.950 --> 00:23:50.940
will not want to eat.

669
00:23:50.940 --> 00:23:52.170
So you may need to think about some

670
00:23:52.170 --> 00:23:53.670
sort of pain control for that.

671
00:23:54.720 --> 00:23:56.403
Ooh, Kawasaki Disease.

672
00:23:57.240 --> 00:23:59.580
Kawasaki Disease is a vasculitis.

673
00:23:59.580 --> 00:24:01.440
We don't know what causes it.

674
00:24:01.440 --> 00:24:02.640
It's the leading cause

675
00:24:02.640 --> 00:24:05.460
of acquired cardiac disease in children.

676
00:24:05.460 --> 00:24:07.710
So, if you have a child who's had a fever

677
00:24:07.710 --> 00:24:09.510
for greater than five days,

678
00:24:09.510 --> 00:24:11.130
think about these other criteria.

679
00:24:11.130 --> 00:24:14.370
So do they have bilateral conjunctivitis?

680
00:24:14.370 --> 00:24:16.230
Do they have erythema of their mouth

681
00:24:16.230 --> 00:24:17.280
that strawberry tongue,

682
00:24:17.280 --> 00:24:18.690
fissuring crusting their lips,

683
00:24:18.690 --> 00:24:21.150
mouth just looks like it's peeling and sore?

684
00:24:21.150 --> 00:24:22.500
Induration of the hands and feet.

685
00:24:22.500 --> 00:24:23.850
So you often see 'em and their hands

686
00:24:23.850 --> 00:24:25.470
are starting to peel and their fingers

687
00:24:25.470 --> 00:24:27.270
are starting to peel off,

688
00:24:27.270 --> 00:24:29.610
the erythematous rash all over the body.

689
00:24:29.610 --> 00:24:32.580
And a big enlarged lymph node mass, 1.5 centimeters.

690
00:24:32.580 --> 00:24:34.950
If you think about it, that's a pretty good size lymph node.

691
00:24:34.950 --> 00:24:36.552
So if you have any of those things,

692
00:24:36.552 --> 00:24:38.670
think, "It's Kawasaki's Disease."

693
00:24:38.670 --> 00:24:41.160
Ooh, so why am I bringing up Kawasaki's Disease?

694
00:24:41.160 --> 00:24:43.710
You know, I saw it maybe once or twice my whole career.

695
00:24:43.710 --> 00:24:44.640
Over the past four years,

696
00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:46.890
I've seen it probably 10 to 15 times.

697
00:24:46.890 --> 00:24:49.230
And that was before we knew about this.

698
00:24:49.230 --> 00:24:51.480
And I'm sure some of you saw this multi-system

699
00:24:51.480 --> 00:24:53.910
inflammatory syndrome in children.

700
00:24:53.910 --> 00:24:57.281
So these were adolescents and kids

701
00:24:57.281 --> 00:24:59.760
under the age of 21 who had a lot of the things

702
00:24:59.760 --> 00:25:02.190
that looked like Kawasaki Disease.

703
00:25:02.190 --> 00:25:05.220
They came in with multisystem organ involvement,

704
00:25:05.220 --> 00:25:07.383
and they had recent COVID-19.

705
00:25:09.772 --> 00:25:11.400
A lot of these,

706
00:25:11.400 --> 00:25:13.890
these kids we thought initially had Kawasaki Disease

707
00:25:13.890 --> 00:25:17.310
until we diagnosed them with MIS-C, MIS-C.

708
00:25:17.310 --> 00:25:19.200
So the risks are the same.

709
00:25:19.200 --> 00:25:21.960
Both of 'em are at risk for coronary artery aneurysms.

710
00:25:21.960 --> 00:25:24.420
For kids with the MIS-C,

711
00:25:24.420 --> 00:25:27.930
they ended up in the PI, Pediatric Intensive Care Unit,

712
00:25:27.930 --> 00:25:31.230
the PICU, with hypertension and shock as well sometimes.

713
00:25:31.230 --> 00:25:32.460
So the treatment is the same.

714
00:25:32.460 --> 00:25:35.550
You give them a single dose of IV immunoglobulin,

715
00:25:35.550 --> 00:25:37.142
you give them low dose aspirin,

716
00:25:37.142 --> 00:25:39.176
you might give them corticosteroids,

717
00:25:39.176 --> 00:25:40.380
some debate about that.

718
00:25:40.380 --> 00:25:42.120
And you do an echo at the beginning,

719
00:25:42.120 --> 00:25:43.440
and then six to eight weeks after.

720
00:25:43.440 --> 00:25:44.820
So if you were to take care of a child

721
00:25:44.820 --> 00:25:46.860
who'd been hospitalized for Kawasaki's,

722
00:25:46.860 --> 00:25:47.766
you would wanna make sure

723
00:25:47.766 --> 00:25:50.460
to follow up on their inflammatory markers

724
00:25:50.460 --> 00:25:52.810
and make sure they had a repeat echocardiogram.

725
00:25:54.450 --> 00:25:56.760
Meningitis, meningococcal meningitis,

726
00:25:56.760 --> 00:25:59.250
if you haven't seen this, it's pretty terrible.

727
00:25:59.250 --> 00:26:01.770
Abrupt onset of fever, chills, malaise.

728
00:26:01.770 --> 00:26:03.780
They have that rash, the macular papular,

729
00:26:03.780 --> 00:26:05.880
macular rash all over their body,

730
00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:10.350
and they can develop DIC, shock and die.

731
00:26:10.350 --> 00:26:12.570
It's not very fun.

732
00:26:12.570 --> 00:26:15.872
Here is the meningitis causes by age.

733
00:26:15.872 --> 00:26:20.550
Again, viruses fortunately are your most common cause.

734
00:26:20.550 --> 00:26:22.890
But you'll notice that in the zero to one month age,

735
00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:24.750
it's those bacteria that we think about

736
00:26:24.750 --> 00:26:26.490
in the newborns group B strep, e-coli,

737
00:26:26.490 --> 00:26:30.060
listeria, one to 23, it's three months.

738
00:26:30.060 --> 00:26:32.400
It's streptococcus pneumonia, listeria,

739
00:26:32.400 --> 00:26:35.031
E. coli, hits sort of a transition period.

740
00:26:35.031 --> 00:26:36.150
After the age of two,

741
00:26:36.150 --> 00:26:38.250
you're in the streptococcus pneumonia,

742
00:26:38.250 --> 00:26:40.140
and neisseria mening is mostly the things

743
00:26:40.140 --> 00:26:41.580
you think about with adults.

744
00:26:41.580 --> 00:26:42.930
And the treatment of course,

745
00:26:42.930 --> 00:26:45.720
is pretty similar to what you would do

746
00:26:45.720 --> 00:26:47.070
for adults in that group.

747
00:26:47.070 --> 00:26:49.440
Younger kids, it's still your amp and gent,

748
00:26:49.440 --> 00:26:51.510
or amp and cefotaxime.

749
00:26:51.510 --> 00:26:53.460
And think about vancomycin.

750
00:26:53.460 --> 00:26:56.610
We never used to think about vancomycin, but now we do.

751
00:26:56.610 --> 00:26:57.990
Okay, frequent flyers.

752
00:26:57.990 --> 00:26:59.220
Community acquired pneumonia.

753
00:26:59.220 --> 00:27:01.701
I can almost guarantee you will see croup and bronchiolitis.

754
00:27:01.701 --> 00:27:04.290
So please take a few minutes and study that.

755
00:27:04.290 --> 00:27:06.570
Kawasaki's, I think with the recurrence of

756
00:27:06.570 --> 00:27:07.860
the MIS-C that came up recently,

757
00:27:07.860 --> 00:27:09.120
it seems to have popped up.

758
00:27:09.120 --> 00:27:10.590
Viral URI Treatment.

759
00:27:10.590 --> 00:27:12.510
Please don't give antibiotics.

760
00:27:12.510 --> 00:27:15.240
Urinary tract infections and the sepsis workup for newborns.

761
00:27:15.240 --> 00:27:17.490
So, here are your answers.

762
00:27:17.490 --> 00:27:19.375
<v Moderator>Thank you very much, Dr. Bestie.</v>

763
00:27:19.375 --> 00:27:22.208
(whimsical chime)

